    "instruction": "Using metric.csv only, perform the following (keep results cached in memory and return compact aggregates only):\n1) For each unique (cmdb_id, kpi_name) compute global P95 and P05 using the full available time series in metric.csv (do NOT pre-filter by time). 2) Filter metric.csv rows to the incident window from '2022-03-20T12:30:00+08:00' to '2022-03-20T12:59:59+08:00' (inclusive). 3) Within the filtered window, mark a row as an anomaly if value >= P95 OR value <= P05 for its (cmdb_id,kpi_name). 4) Produce two compact outputs: A) Top 20 (cmdb_id,kpi_name) combos ranked by anomaly count (fields for each combo: cmdb_id, kpi_name, anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp, max_value_in_window, global_P95, global_P05). B) Top 10 cmdb_id (component) aggregated by total anomaly_count (fields: cmdb_id, total_anomaly_count, earliest_anomaly_timestamp_over_all_KPIs). Limit returned rows to these counts. Return results as dictionaries/lists; do not print full time series."
}

{
    "analysis": "We have metric-level anomalies across many components during the whole 12:30–13:00 window. Top aggregated anomaly counts highlight adservice/adservice2 and multiple frontend pods; shippingservice2-0 shows many container filesystem/node metrics at constant edge values. To pinpoint two distinct failure occurrences and localize root causes we need temporal clustering and cross-check with traces/logs. The next focused step should identify when the system experienced concentrated error messages (error_logs) to find candidate failure timestamps and inspect their messages and affected pods. This will narrow down failure times for subsequent metric/trace drilling.",
